<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="4" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="3.[264,1323,591,1897]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<emphasis box="[264,383,591,616]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Males of the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[713,858,591,616]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Lomachaeta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[713,858,591,616]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Lomachaeta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from other Sphaeropthalmina by the presence of an apical row of stout, lanceolate bristles on metasomal segments 
<number box="[435,482,671,697]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="3.5" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="2.0">2–5</number>
, which are directed obliquely inwards (
<figureCitation box="[954,1025,671,697]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 5. 1 – 2" captionStartId="23.[264,382,1768,1792]" captionTargetBox="[354,1305,376,1727]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[245,1341,329,1763]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 5. 1 – 2, Lomachaeta hicksi ♂, 1. first and second metasomal segment, dorsal view; 2. wing; 3. L. chionothrix, male genitalia, dorsal and lateral view, scale = 0.25 mm; 4. L. cirrhomeris, male genitalia, dorsal and lateral view, scale = 0.25 mm; 5. L. hicksi, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/157429/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Fig. 
<number box="[1011,1025,671,697]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
). Females of this genus can be distinguished from other 
<taxonomicName box="[658,780,711,737]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Mutillidae</taxonomicName>
by the following combination of characters: presence of subovate eyes, presence of a reticulated surface on the head and mesosoma (
<figureCitation box="[273,345,791,817]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 5. 1 – 2" captionStartId="23.[264,382,1768,1792]" captionTargetBox="[354,1305,376,1727]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[245,1341,329,1763]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 5. 1 – 2, Lomachaeta hicksi ♂, 1. first and second metasomal segment, dorsal view; 2. wing; 3. L. chionothrix, male genitalia, dorsal and lateral view, scale = 0.25 mm; 4. L. cirrhomeris, male genitalia, dorsal and lateral view, scale = 0.25 mm; 5. L. hicksi, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/157429/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Fig. 
<number box="[329,345,791,817]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
), absence of carinae defining the lateral margins of the pygidial area, presence of apically edentate mandibles, a petiolate first metasomal segment (
<figureCitation box="[1040,1111,831,857]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 5. 1 – 2" captionStartId="23.[264,382,1768,1792]" captionTargetBox="[354,1305,376,1727]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[245,1341,329,1763]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 5. 1 – 2, Lomachaeta hicksi ♂, 1. first and second metasomal segment, dorsal view; 2. wing; 3. L. chionothrix, male genitalia, dorsal and lateral view, scale = 0.25 mm; 4. L. cirrhomeris, male genitalia, dorsal and lateral view, scale = 0.25 mm; 5. L. hicksi, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/157429/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Fig. 
<number box="[1095,1111,831,857]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
), and presence of tuberculate propodeal spiracles (
<figureCitation box="[644,716,871,897]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 5. 1 – 2" captionStartId="23.[264,382,1768,1792]" captionTargetBox="[354,1305,376,1727]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[245,1341,329,1763]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 5. 1 – 2, Lomachaeta hicksi ♂, 1. first and second metasomal segment, dorsal view; 2. wing; 3. L. chionothrix, male genitalia, dorsal and lateral view, scale = 0.25 mm; 4. L. cirrhomeris, male genitalia, dorsal and lateral view, scale = 0.25 mm; 5. L. hicksi, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/157429/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Fig. 
<number box="[699,716,871,897]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[264,1323,591,1897]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
The following additional characters will help differentiate 
<taxonomicName box="[1035,1180,911,936]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Lomachaeta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1035,1180,911,936]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Lomachaeta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from other Sphaeropthalmina: males having a tridentate mandible with a ventral tooth or slight excision that is angulate medially, lacking parapsidal lines and notauli, having an inconspicuous pterostigma (
<figureCitation box="[471,545,1031,1057]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 5. 1 – 2" captionStartId="23.[264,382,1768,1792]" captionTargetBox="[354,1305,376,1727]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[245,1341,329,1763]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 5. 1 – 2, Lomachaeta hicksi ♂, 1. first and second metasomal segment, dorsal view; 2. wing; 3. L. chionothrix, male genitalia, dorsal and lateral view, scale = 0.25 mm; 4. L. cirrhomeris, male genitalia, dorsal and lateral view, scale = 0.25 mm; 5. L. hicksi, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/157429/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Fig. 
<number box="[528,545,1031,1057]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
), having a distinctly petiolate first metasomal segment, having a hypopygium that is rounded apically but bidentate medially, having reduced wing venation in comparison with other New World species (
<figureCitation box="[816,889,1111,1137]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 5. 1 – 2" captionStartId="23.[264,382,1768,1792]" captionTargetBox="[354,1305,376,1727]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[245,1341,329,1763]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 5. 1 – 2, Lomachaeta hicksi ♂, 1. first and second metasomal segment, dorsal view; 2. wing; 3. L. chionothrix, male genitalia, dorsal and lateral view, scale = 0.25 mm; 4. L. cirrhomeris, male genitalia, dorsal and lateral view, scale = 0.25 mm; 5. L. hicksi, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/157429/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Fig. 
<number box="[872,889,1111,1137]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
), and having the cuspis reduced to a knob­like structure (
<figureCitation box="[501,644,1151,1177]" captionStart="FIGURES 14 – 23" captionStartId="25.[264,382,1744,1768]" captionTargetBox="[268,1316,324,1670]" captionTargetId="figure@25.[254,1331,306,1696]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURES 14 – 23. Internal view of male genitalia, 14. Lomachaeta chionothrix; 15. L. cirrhomeris; 16. L. hicksi; 17. L. hicksi; 18. L. hicksi; 19. L. ptilohyalus; 20. L. crocopinna; 21. L. hyphantria; 22. L. hicksi; 23. Smicromutilla beadugrimi; scale = 0.20 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/157431/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Figs. 
<number box="[566,644,1151,1177]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="18.0" valueMax="22.0" valueMin="14.0">14–22</number>
</figureCitation>
); females having a genal carina and a pyriform mesosoma (widest anteriorly and gradually narrowing posteriorly) (
<figureCitation box="[925,997,1191,1217]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 5. 1 – 2" captionStartId="23.[264,382,1768,1792]" captionTargetBox="[354,1305,376,1727]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[245,1341,329,1763]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 5. 1 – 2, Lomachaeta hicksi ♂, 1. first and second metasomal segment, dorsal view; 2. wing; 3. L. chionothrix, male genitalia, dorsal and lateral view, scale = 0.25 mm; 4. L. cirrhomeris, male genitalia, dorsal and lateral view, scale = 0.25 mm; 5. L. hicksi, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/157429/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Fig. 
<number box="[980,997,1191,1217]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[264,1323,591,1897]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
The genitalia of male 
<taxonomicName box="[569,714,1231,1256]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Lomachaeta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[569,714,1231,1256]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Lomachaeta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are of limited taxonomic use because they are quite similar between species (
<figureCitation box="[563,670,1271,1297]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 5. 1 – 2" captionStartId="23.[264,382,1768,1792]" captionTargetBox="[354,1305,376,1727]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[245,1341,329,1763]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 5. 1 – 2, Lomachaeta hicksi ♂, 1. first and second metasomal segment, dorsal view; 2. wing; 3. L. chionothrix, male genitalia, dorsal and lateral view, scale = 0.25 mm; 4. L. cirrhomeris, male genitalia, dorsal and lateral view, scale = 0.25 mm; 5. L. hicksi, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/157429/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Figs. 3,4</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[685,763,1271,1297]" captionStart="FIGURES 14 – 23" captionStartId="25.[264,382,1744,1768]" captionTargetBox="[268,1316,324,1670]" captionTargetId="figure@25.[254,1331,306,1696]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURES 14 – 23. Internal view of male genitalia, 14. Lomachaeta chionothrix; 15. L. cirrhomeris; 16. L. hicksi; 17. L. hicksi; 18. L. hicksi; 19. L. ptilohyalus; 20. L. crocopinna; 21. L. hyphantria; 22. L. hicksi; 23. Smicromutilla beadugrimi; scale = 0.20 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/157431/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<number box="[685,763,1271,1297]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="18.0" valueMax="22.0" valueMin="14.0">14–22</number>
</figureCitation>
). The genitalia, however, along with the presence or absence of a ventral mandibular tooth, do suggest several relationships. The following three species groups are defined by male characters: 
<taxonomicName box="[980,1144,1351,1376]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Lomachaeta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crocopinna">
<emphasis box="[980,1144,1351,1376]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">L. crocopinna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species­group, 
<taxonomicName box="[264,363,1391,1416]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Lomachaeta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hicksi">
<emphasis box="[264,363,1391,1416]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">L. hicksi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species­group and 
<taxonomicName box="[590,750,1391,1416]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Lomachaeta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hyphantria">
<emphasis box="[590,750,1391,1416]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">L. hyphantria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species­group.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[264,1323,591,1897]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
The 
<taxonomicName box="[367,533,1431,1456]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Lomachaeta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crocopinna">
<emphasis box="[367,533,1431,1456]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">L. crocopinna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species­group is defined by lack of the ventral mandibular tooth, presence of distinctly brachyplumose pubescence, and presence of long setae on the ventral margin of the parameres (
<figureCitation box="[625,774,1511,1537]" captionStart="FIGURES 14 – 23" captionStartId="25.[264,382,1744,1768]" captionTargetBox="[268,1316,324,1670]" captionTargetId="figure@25.[254,1331,306,1696]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURES 14 – 23. Internal view of male genitalia, 14. Lomachaeta chionothrix; 15. L. cirrhomeris; 16. L. hicksi; 17. L. hicksi; 18. L. hicksi; 19. L. ptilohyalus; 20. L. crocopinna; 21. L. hyphantria; 22. L. hicksi; 23. Smicromutilla beadugrimi; scale = 0.20 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/157431/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Figs. 19, 20</figureCitation>
), and includes 
<emphasis box="[959,1132,1511,1536]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<taxonomicName box="[959,1128,1511,1536]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Lomachaeta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crocopinna" status="sp. nov.">L. crocopinna</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1143,1237,1511,1537]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Lomachaeta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ptilohyalus" status="sp. nov.">L. ptilohyalus</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[409,499,1551,1577]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="5" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="3.[264,1323,591,1897]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
The 
<taxonomicName box="[364,523,1591,1616]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Lomachaeta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hyphantria">
<emphasis box="[364,523,1591,1616]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">L. hyphantria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species­group is defined by the lack of the ventral mandibular tooth, presence of indistinct brachyplumose pubescence (serrate), presence of confluent punctures on the mesonotum (
<figureCitation box="[565,652,1671,1697]" captionStart="FIGURES 6 – 13. 6 – 12" captionStartId="24.[264,382,1753,1777]" captionTargetBox="[324,1304,358,1675]" captionTargetId="figure@24.[256,1330,326,1729]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURES 6 – 13. 6 – 12, Pronotum and mesonotum of males, dorsal view of left half, not to same scale, 6. Lomachaeta chionothrix; 7. L. cirrhomeris; 8. L. hicksi; 9. L. hicksi; 10. L. hicksi; 11. L. hicksi; 12. L. ptilohyalus. 13. Mesonotum of L. hyphantria, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/157430/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Fig. 
<number box="[621,652,1671,1697]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="13.0">13</number>
</figureCitation>
), and absence of long setae on the ventral margin of the parameres (
<figureCitation box="[400,487,1711,1737]" captionStart="FIGURES 14 – 23" captionStartId="25.[264,382,1744,1768]" captionTargetBox="[268,1316,324,1670]" captionTargetId="figure@25.[254,1331,306,1696]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURES 14 – 23. Internal view of male genitalia, 14. Lomachaeta chionothrix; 15. L. cirrhomeris; 16. L. hicksi; 17. L. hicksi; 18. L. hicksi; 19. L. ptilohyalus; 20. L. crocopinna; 21. L. hyphantria; 22. L. hicksi; 23. Smicromutilla beadugrimi; scale = 0.20 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/157431/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Fig. 
<number box="[455,487,1711,1737]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="21.0">21</number>
</figureCitation>
), and includes only 
<emphasis box="[723,890,1711,1736]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<taxonomicName box="[723,886,1711,1736]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Lomachaeta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hyphantria" status="sp. nov.">L. hyphantria</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[897,988,1711,1737]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[264,1323,591,1897]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
The 
<taxonomicName box="[364,463,1751,1776]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Lomachaeta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hicksi">
<emphasis box="[364,463,1751,1776]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">L. hicksi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species­group is defined by presence of a ventral mandibular tooth, presence of indistinct brachyplumose pubescence (serrate), and absence of long setae on the ventral margin of the parameres (
<figureCitation box="[652,837,1831,1857]" captionStart="FIGURES 14 – 23" captionStartId="25.[264,382,1744,1768]" captionTargetBox="[268,1316,324,1670]" captionTargetId="figure@25.[254,1331,306,1696]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURES 14 – 23. Internal view of male genitalia, 14. Lomachaeta chionothrix; 15. L. cirrhomeris; 16. L. hicksi; 17. L. hicksi; 18. L. hicksi; 19. L. ptilohyalus; 20. L. crocopinna; 21. L. hyphantria; 22. L. hicksi; 23. Smicromutilla beadugrimi; scale = 0.20 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/157431/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Figs. 
<number box="[718,748,1831,1857]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="14.0">14</number>
–18, 22
</figureCitation>
) and includes 
<taxonomicName box="[1008,1173,1831,1856]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Lomachaeta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chionothrix">
<emphasis box="[1008,1173,1831,1856]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">L. chionothrix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Lomachaeta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cirrhomeris">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">L. cirrhomeris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[365,464,1871,1896]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Lomachaeta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hicksi">
<emphasis box="[365,464,1871,1896]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">L. hicksi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[264,1323,284,830]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
The males of 
<emphasis box="[472,728,284,309]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<taxonomicName box="[472,595,284,309]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Lomachaeta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="argenta">L. argenta</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[607,724,284,309]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Lomachaeta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ibarrai">L. ibarrai</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[785,889,284,309]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Lomachaeta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vianai">
<emphasis box="[785,889,284,309]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">L. vianai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
remain unknown. As such, this species are not placed into species­groups, because the species­groups defined above are based on characters derived from males.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[264,1323,284,830]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<emphasis box="[312,379,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Hosts</emphasis>
. Host data suggests that 
<taxonomicName box="[708,853,404,429]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Lomachaeta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[708,853,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Lomachaeta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species are opportunistic parasitoids. Rearing parasitoids from twig and trap nests provided new host records for four more species of 
<taxonomicName box="[351,496,484,509]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Lomachaeta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[351,496,484,509]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Lomachaeta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Host data suggests that the species may be limited to cavity nesting hosts of small size, including 
<taxonomicName authority="Spinola" authorityName="Spinola" box="[614,823,524,550]" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" genus="Solierella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[614,727,524,549]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Solierella</emphasis>
Spinola
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Fox" authorityName="Fox" box="[839,1019,524,550]" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" genus="Pisonopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[839,966,524,549]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Pisonopsis</emphasis>
Fox
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Latreille. Specific" authorityName="Latreille. Specific" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" genus="Trypoxylon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1076,1208,524,549]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Trypoxylon</emphasis>
Latreille. Specific
</taxonomicName>
hosts are listed under each 
<taxonomicName box="[684,829,564,589]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Lomachaeta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[684,829,564,589]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Lomachaeta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species. It is noteworthy that the females of the species­group lack a distinct pygidium, as do many twig nesting sphecoid wasps, bees, and their hymenopteran parasitoids, such as mutillid species of the 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Sphaeropthalma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="uro">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Sphaeropthalma uro</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species­group.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="4.[264,1323,284,830]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<emphasis box="[312,455,724,749]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Distribution</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[473,618,724,749]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Lomachaeta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[473,618,724,749]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Lomachaeta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
ranges throughout the 
<collectingCountry box="[902,1064,724,750]" name="United States of America" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">United States</collectingCountry>
, south to 
<collectingCountry box="[1187,1317,724,750]" name="Guatemala" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Guatemala</collectingCountry>
, and is also found in 
<collectingCountry box="[501,618,764,790]" name="Argentina" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Argentina</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[674,764,764,790]" name="Bolivia" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
. It is likely that 
<taxonomicName box="[962,1107,764,789]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Lomachaeta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[962,1107,764,789]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Lomachaeta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs along with its hosts throughout the Neotropics.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
